name: Abbey Hill Steps
description:
Guest Artist Series//

Back by popular demand.. 

We are delighted to announce that we will be launching the series with 4x new designs by Tommy Perman.

Tommy Perman is an artist from Edinburgh. He's probably best known for being part of the arts collective / band FOUND who are responsible for the creation of an emotional musical robot called Cybraphon. But in January Tommy became a dad and decided that the music industry's a young man's game and so he quit the band to concentrate on his own work. For the last few months Tommy has taken early morning walks with his son Patrick strapped to his chest, taking loads of photos along the way. He then returns home and draws from these photos. 

These four tees are part of a new series called Decompositions in which Tommy deconstructs familiar objects to create new abstract designs. With deconstructed front and back print reveal.

Steps, Abbeyhill

"This design was the first in the series. The steps are attached to a building of a housing estate that most people probably find quite ugly but that I really love. The Abbeyhill estate has a great situation opposite Holyrood Palace and the Scottish Parliament. In an odd way the estate reminds me of a village clinging to a rocky Greek island – with many different angles that catch the sun and create striking shadows."

name: Asda Bollards
description:
Guest Artist Series//

Back by popular demand...

We are delighted to announce that we will be launching the series with 4x new designs by Tommy Perman.

Tommy Perman is an artist from Edinburgh. He's probably best known for being part of the arts collective / band FOUND who are responsible for the creation of an emotional musical robot called Cybraphon. But in January Tommy became a dad and decided that the music industry's a young man's game and so he quit the band to concentrate on his own work. For the last few months Tommy has taken early morning walks with his son Patrick strapped to his chest, taking loads of photos along the way. He then returns home and draws from these photos. 

These four tees are part of a new series called Decompositions in which Tommy deconstructs familiar objects to create new abstract designs. With deconstructed front and back print reveal.

Bollards, Sandpiper Drive (Newhaven Asda)

"These bollards are on the romantically named Sandpiper Drive down near Newhaven harbour. In reality it's not a particularly nice area – there's a giant Asda, some very ugly new buildings and some decaying old buildings – but these bollards with their pleasing colours, geometric shadows and nice perspective really did it for me.

name: Leith Walk Speed Camera
description:

For the last few months Tommy has taken early morning walks with his son Patrick strapped to his chest, taking loads of photos along the way. He then returns home and draws from these photos. 

These four tees are part of a new series called Decompositions in which Tommy deconstructs familiar objects to create new abstract designs. With deconstructed front and back print reveal.

Speed Camera, Leith Walk

"This speed camera is situated outside my local Scotmid supermarket on Leith Walk. I'm a big fan of stripes and bright colours and how they are used in street furniture. I also think this speed camera resembles a kind of techno owl."

name: Dean Gallery Litter Bin
description:
Guest Artist Series//

Back by popular demand...

We are delighted to announce that we will be launching the series with 4x new designs by Tommy Perman.

Tommy Perman is an artist from Edinburgh. He's probably best known for being part of the arts collective / band FOUND who are responsible for the creation of an emotional musical robot called Cybraphon. But in January Tommy became a dad and decided that the music industry's a young man's game and so he quit the band to concentrate on his own work. For the last few months Tommy has taken early morning walks with his son Patrick strapped to his chest, taking loads of photos along the way. He then returns home and draws from these photos. 

These four tees are part of a new series called Decompositions in which Tommy deconstructs familiar objects to create new abstract designs. With deconstructed front and back print reveal.

Litter Bin, Dean Gallery

"The Dean Gallery (or Modern Two as it's now known) is one of my favourite places in Edinburgh. I love walking along the Water of Leith walkway to get to this gallery. This litter bin caught my eye because of it's pleasing green colour scheme that has clearly been designed to fit in with the tastefully landscaped grounds of the gallery. None of the standard black plastic bins here!"
